{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits and potential drawbacks of reducing tillage on European farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "The documented benefits of reducing tillage on European farmland include positive effects on soil organisms, with four European studies finding more microbes, more species of earthworm, or higher microbe activity under reduced tillage. Soil health improvements are consistently reported, with twelve studies from Europe and other regions finding higher soil organic carbon in soils under no-tillage or reduced tillage systems compared to conventionally tilled soil. Eight studies found maintained or increased soil organic matter and improved soil structure under reduced tillage, while four trials found higher nutrient retention. Erosion control benefits are documented, with seven European and international trials showing reduced soil loss and runoff under reduced tillage compared to conventional ploughing. However, potential drawbacks include increased soil compaction, with three replicated trials from Europe finding higher compaction under reduced tillage. Water management challenges are noted, with three European trials finding that conventional ploughing and sub-soiling improved the soil's ability to absorb water and increased soil water content. Yield impacts show mixed results, with one replicated study finding lower yields under minimum or no-tillage compared to conventional tillage. Some studies found negative effects on certain wildlife, with twenty-six studies from nine European countries finding reducing tillage had either negative, no effect, or no consistent effects on abundance, biomass, or species richness of some invertebrates, earthworm abundance, biomass, or species richness, mammal abundance, and some bird species.",
