  "relevant_summary": "For solitary bees on European farmland, 29 out of 30 replicated trials across 10 countries (including Europe) showed that artificial nest boxes were occupied by bees. Many species readily nest in boxes, including some considered endangered in Germany. On agricultural land specifically, three trials demonstrated that the number of occupied solitary bee nests can double over three years with repeated nest box provision. One trial in German farmland showed that four medium to large European solitary bee species have foraging ranges of 150-600 m, requiring nest boxes to be within this distance of foraging resources. However, 11 replicated trials recorded bees in nest boxes being attacked by parasites or predators, with mortality rates ranging from 2-56%. Two trials in California showed that non-native European earwigs and introduced European leafcutter bee species can occupy boxes more frequently than native bees.\n\nFor birds on European farmland, two studies from the Netherlands and UK found increases in Eurasian kestrel clutches and breeding tree sparrows following nest box provision, while eight studies from Finland, Netherlands, Sweden, Switzerland and UK found agricultural nest boxes were occupied by various species including Eurasian kestrel, long-eared owl, common starling, tits, tree sparrow, stock dove, jackdaw, Eurasian wryneck and Eurasian hoopoe. Nest success was related to pasture availability and boxes positioned higher above ground had higher occupancy and reproductive success.",
