{
  "query": "For managing heather moorland in the UK, what is the comparative evidence for the effectiveness of swiping versus controlled burning on plant diversity?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on a replicated controlled trial in Northern Ireland, heather Moorland managed through flailing (swiping) to simulate burning had more plant species eight years after management compared to control unflailed plots, but fewer plant species than burned plots (Action 151). The same study found that heather moorland subject to a single controlled burn had more plant species eight years after management than control unburned plots (Action 152). This indicates that while swiping can increase plant diversity compared to no management, controlled burning may be more effective at promoting plant species richness than swiping in UK heather moorland management.\n\nEvidence also suggests that cutting to control bracken can increase the species richness of heathland plant species (Action 1653), though the effects may vary depending on the specific vegetation being managed. Overall, the available evidence suggests that controlled burning appears to be more effective than swiping for maximizing plant diversity in heather moorland management in the UK.",
  "action_ids": [
