  "relevant_summary": "Seventeen studies from the UK found that uncropped, cultivated margins provide significant wildlife benefits. These include increased species richness of plants and bumblebees, increased abundance of spiders, ground-dwelling invertebrates and ground beetles, and establishment of rare arable plant species (Action 562). Bird species including northern lapwing, Eurasian skylark, stone curlew, grey partridge and yellow wagtail successfully bred in lapwing plots (Actions 562, 213). Three studies found that farms with uncropped cultivated margins showed similar or higher butterfly species richness and abundance compared to conventional farms (Action 3923). Two studies found that nesting success of birds was higher in lapwing plots compared to crops (Action 213).\n\nHowever, two UK studies found that leaving these plots had no effect on 11 out of 12 farmland bird species or ground beetles (Action 562). One review found evidence that pernicious weeds were more commonly found on uncropped cultivated margins than conservation or conventional headlands (Action 562). Studies found concerning effects on grey partridge populations - the proportion of young partridges in the population was lower in areas with high proportions of uncropped cultivated margins, and grey partridge productivity was not related to the amount of lapwing plots on a site (Actions 562, 213). A few studies noted that the value of naturally regenerated margins was based on thistle species considered to be pernicious weeds requiring control, and that the value for wildlife was not consistent from year to year (Action 20).",
